    <h2>Top Reasons to Visit Japan</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Cultural Heritage:</strong> Kyoto‚Äôs temples, like the <strong>Golden Pavilion (Kinkaku-ji)</strong> and <strong>Fushimi Inari Shrine</strong>, offer a unique glimpse into Japan‚Äôs ancient traditions.</li>
        <img src="https://facts.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/18-fascinating-facts-about-fushimi-inari-taisha-1694668911.jpg" alt="fushimi inari shrine" style="width: 600px; height: auto;">
        <li><strong>Modern Innovation:</strong> Tokyo is the future of urban life, with attractions like <strong>teamLab Borderless</strong>, an immersive digital art museum that uses lights and projections to create interactive experiences.</li>
        <li><strong>Unique Theme Parks:</strong> <strong>Tokyo DisneySea</strong> is the only Disney park in the world with a nautical theme, and <strong>Universal Studios Japan</strong> in Osaka offers exclusive attractions like <strong>Super Nintendo World</strong> and <strong>The Wizarding World of Harry Potter</strong>.</li>
        <li><strong>Nightlife in Shinjuku:</strong> If you‚Äôre in your 20s, <strong>Shinjuku</strong> is a must-visit for nightlife. Whether you‚Äôre exploring the quirky bars in <strong>Golden Gai</strong> or experiencing karaoke in <strong>Kabukicho</strong>, the energy of Shinjuku at night is unforgettable.</li>
        <img src="https://umamibites.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/shinjukumain.jpg" alt="shinjuku at night" style="width: 600px; height: auto;">
        <li><strong>Shopping & Food:</strong> Japan is home to incredible shopping experiences, like the famous <strong>Don Quijote</strong> (Donki), where you can find everything from electronics to souvenirs. Combined with Japan‚Äôs exceptional food scene, it‚Äôs easy to spend more than expected, even though the yen is lower than the Canadian dollar.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Getting There and Moving Around Japan</h2>
    <p>Thanks to my part-time role at Air Canada, I‚Äôve been able to take advantage of convenient direct flights from Canadian cities like Toronto, Vancouver, and Montreal to Japan‚Äôs main airports: <strong>Tokyo Narita</strong>, <strong>Haneda</strong>, and <strong>Kansai International (Osaka)</strong>. Air Canada offers round-trip flights that typically range from <strong>$1,300 to $2,000 CAD</strong>, depending on the season. Bookings can be made on   
          <a href="https://www.aircanada.com/home/ca/en/aco/flights" target="_blank">Air Canada Offical Website.</a>
    </p>
    
    <p>Once you arrive in Japan, the transportation system is one of the best in the world. The <strong>Shinkansen (bullet train)</strong> makes it easy to travel between cities like Tokyo, Kyoto, and Osaka. A <strong>Japan Rail Pass</strong>, priced at approximately <strong>$375 CAD</strong> for 7 days, provides unlimited travel on most major train lines.</p>
    <img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:825/0*pkfxwvdtF3I45dBX.jpg" alt="shinkansen bullet train passing through mount fuji from tokyo to osaka" style="width: 600px; height: auto;">
    <p>For local travel within cities, subways and buses are affordable, with fares usually between <strong>$3 and $5 CAD</strong> per ride. If you‚Äôll be using public transport frequently, I recommend getting the <strong>Sanrio Pasmo Pass</strong>, which doubles as a practical transportation card and a cute souvenir featuring famous <strong>Sanrio characters</strong> like Hello Kitty.</p>
<img src="https://www.pasmo.co.jp/global/assets/webp/img-pasmoPassport.webp" alt="sanrio pasmo pass" style="width: 600px; height: auto;">

